{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e75594bd-ef42-43ad-a64e-2e1caad89e91","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on Kubernetes:\n\n### 1. Exec into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present)\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find the process ID\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect the trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### Alternative: `dotnet-counters` for a quick look first\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-counters\ndotnet-counters monitor -p <PID> --counters System.Runtime\n```\nThis gives live CPU/GC/thread stats without a full trace.\n\n### Getting the file out\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:/app/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n> **Tip:** If `dotnet tool install` fails due to no SDK in the container, copy the standalone `dotnet-trace` binary in, or use `PerfView /LogFile=trace.etl` from the **host node** targeting the container's process (since you have admin on the host, Windows container processes are visible on the host).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"aa49c7e1-f7c5-4edf-ac99-2769f2b6380d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes, where they're experiencing high CPU. This is a troubleshooting/advisory question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise guidance.","outputTokens":435,"requestId":"9441:1300AE:1D9A81:2333D7:69E81D53"},"id":"f4a4ff7a-4fa3-4906-a0c0-aa29b9204f61","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:59:09.356Z","parentId":"1610143a-e09a-43eb-8eec-702500269224"}
